scenario_purpose: The European Interoperability Framework(EIF) provides guidance to public administrations on how to improve governance of their interoperability activities, establish cross-organisational relationships, streamline processes supporting end-to-end digital services, and ensure that existing and new legislation do not compromise interoperability efforts.This CAMSS Scenario allows to assess the compliance of interoperability specifications with the EIF. The objective of the obtained assessment is to determine the suitability of the assessed interoperability specification for the delivery of interoperable European public services.
criterion_description: The standard or specification has been included in a national catalogue from a Member State whose NIF is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the EIF according to NIFO factsheets.
statement:
ASiC is included in the Dutch national catalogue of recommended specifications. The National Interoperability Framework (NIF) of the Netherlands is fully aligned with at least 4 out of 5 sections of the European Interoperability Framework (EIF) according to the National Interoperability Framework Observatory (NIFO) factsheets.
See:
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/collection/national-interoperability-framework-observatory-nifo/nifo-factsheets

criterion_description: All stakeholders have the opportunity to contribute to the development of the specification
statement:
ETSI’s standards-making process has been clearly defined after years of experience. The organisation has adopted the open approach which means direct participation and consensus as a basis to develop standards. All the stakeholders have the opportunity to participate directly in the process of standardisation through the technical committees created to develop ETSI’s technical specifications and standards. The decision-making process includes a public review, where stakeholders involved can provide technical feedback in order to enhance and maximize the quality and accuracy of the standards. 
See: 
https://www.etsi.org/standards/standards-making

criterion_description: The standard or specification is sufficiently mature and has sufficient market acceptance for its use in the development of products and services.
statement:
The last version of the specification was released in 2003 by ETSI’s Technical Committee Electronic Signatures and Infrastructures (ESI). ASiC Baseline profile is linked to the development of ASiC, evolving at the same time. As well, is worth to note that all ETSI standards are focused on market needs ensuring its market acceptance. 
Moreover, its selection in European initiatives demonstrates its maturity for the development of products and services.

criterion_description: The standard or specification fosters the creation of innovative solutions.
statement: ASiC Baseline profile is a specification that defines a set of features needed for the successful creation of containers containing data and information related to eSignatures. The specification performance is closely related to the different specifications involved in electronic signatures across borders. (E.g. CAdEs Baseline Profile, XAdES Baseline Profile). In the context of the European internal market, it can be considered as an asset for the creation of solutions enhancing the interoperability between administrations and businesses when eSignature is needed.

criterion_description: The standard or specification is independent from any specific technology and/or platform.
statement: ASiC Baseline profile depends on the different electronic signature standards (CAdES, PAdES, XAdES), and its settings regarding the level of conformity to provide a convenient result. Even though all the specifications above mentioned are interrelated, each one takes into account the others avoiding interoperability issues by indicating the requirements of each use case.

criterion_description: The standard or specification is proportionate to the needs of its users (citizens, businesses or administrations).
statement: ASiC Baseline Profile provides basic features needed to overcome barriers in the accomplishment of signed data interchange across borders. By providing different levels of conformity according to data transaction needs, it is highly scalable without hampering the interoperability between actors involved.

criterion_description: The standard or specification fosters data portability between systems and applications supporting the implementation and evolution of European public services when legally possible.
statement: The specification assessed is focused on signed data transactions across borders, which means data portability. Moreover, as before mentioned, the scalability and adaptability of specification allow successful data exchange and reuse enhancing the interoperability of systems.

criterion_description: The standard or specification eases the implementation of the once-only principle.
statement:
By allowing to gather different objects signed with electronic signatures in one single ZIP file fosters the implementation of the once-only principle. Moreover, it is included in the context of the Connect Europe Facility’s (CEF) as one of the specifications covering the eSignature Building Block. At the same time, it is implemented in the Digital Signature Services (DSS), across borders initiative which aims to enhance the interoperability and data reuse. 

See:
https://ec.europa.eu/cefdigital/wiki/display/CEFDIGITAL/Services+eSignature

statement: The implementation of eSignature is a mean that allows administrations and stakeholders to exchange digital data reducing the amount of non-digital documents exchanged. Additionally, it fosters the reuse of data across borders, which as well takes part on the administrative burden reduction.

criterion_description: The standard or specification fosters the long-term preservation of electronic records and other kinds of information.
statement: ASiC Baseline Profile is not directly related to the long-term preservation of electronic records or other items. Despite this, according to its purpose of ease the signed data, ASiC Baseline Profile has three level of conformance and the last one is the Long-Term Profile. In the case of the assessed specification, it does not include the profile in itself but invokes the requirements from CAdES and XAdES. Therefore, it helps to ensure the availability of electronic signatures over long time periods, easing interactions between administrations and stakeholders.

statement:
ASiC Baseline Profile is already associated with EIRA ABBs in the European Library Of Specifications (ELIS). Specifically, ASiC Baseline Profile can define the interoperability aspects of “e-Seal Creation Service”, “e-Seal Verification and Validation Service”, “e-Signature Creation Service”, and “e-signature Verification and Validation Service” ABBs of the EIRA Technical View.
See: 
https://joinup.ec.europa.eu/solution/elis/distribution/eliscataloguev100betaxlsx

criterion_description: Mechanisms to assess conformity of the implementations of the standard or specification (e.g. conformity tests, certifications) are available for free.
statement:
ETSI has provided a conformance testing tool for electronic signatures according to the European Commission Mandate 460. The conformity testing tool involves different standards applied in the development of eSignatures, including PAdES, CAdES, XAdES, and ASiC ant their respective Baseline profiles. 

See:
https://signatures-conformance-checker.etsi.org/pub/ASiCConformanceTestChecker_v1.0.pdf

criterion_description: The standard or specification has been selected for its use in a EU cross-border project or initiative after agreed identification and assessment.
statement:
ASiC Baseline profile has been selected within the CEF Digital Signature Service (hereby DSS), along with CAdES, XAdES and PAdES Baseline profiles.  

Digital Signature Service is an open-source software library for electronic signature creation and validation supporting the interoperability of electronic signatures. The initiative is an enabler for cross borders interoperability between administrations and businesses.

See: 
https://ec.europa.eu/cefdigital/wiki/display/CEFDIGITAL/Standards+and+specifications
https://ec.europa.eu/cefdigital/DSS/webapp-demo/doc/dss-documentation.html

statement:
ASiC and ASiC Baseline profile is referenced in the ETSI collection at the European Platform Joinup. Moreover, it can be found for free at ETSI’s webpage
See:
